  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strengthening the Rule of Law in Iraq</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Iraqi torture survivors, prisoners, human rights advocates</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The goal of this program is to strengthen the rule of law and increase human rights protections in Iraq by engaging civil society, legal advocates, and human rights defenders to facilitate implementation of the United Nations Convention against Torture and Other Cruel, Inhuman, or Degrading Treatment or Punishment (CAT).</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">With support from the Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor (DRL), HAI launched an advocacy campaign designed to sensitize government actors to and empower civil society around international legislation against the use of torture.  The project included three high-level meetings with government officials and civil society actors in Erbil.  Furthermore, the project saw the broadcasting of public service announcements on Iraqi Kurdistan radio and television.  HAI provided legal representation, counseling, and psychosocial support to Iraqi survivors of torture seeking treatment and redress.  HAI&apos;s legal and mental health implementing partners continue to make steady progress in identifying clients in need of legal and psychosocial services related to torture.  Furthermore, HAI has conducted intensive training for medical trainers and advocates on recognizing signs and evidence of torture to treat patients and effectively represent them.</narrative>
  </description>
